The Files class, for reading and writing.

Where a path is just a name, the files class is where the actual input and output happens. It is a utility class full of static methods that all operate on a path, and it is your one-stop shop for filesystem work. The high-level methods cover the vast majority of what you will ever need.

For metadata, files dot exists tells you whether something is there, files dot size gives you the byte count, and files dot is-directory checks the kind. For reading text, you have two whole-file methods: read-string pulls the entire file into a single string, and read-all-lines pulls it into a list of strings. For writing, write-string and write take your content and create the file, or truncate and overwrite it if it already exists. And there is read-all-bytes for binary data.

Now, the one distinction that really matters here is whole-file versus lazy. Read-string and read-all-lines are simple, but they load the entire file into memory at once, so they are only appropriate for files you know are small. For a potentially huge file, you use files dot lines, which returns a lazy stream of strings that reads from disk on demand, one line at a time, so your memory stays flat no matter how big the file is. The catch is that this stream holds an open file handle, so you must wrap it in try-with-resources to guarantee the handle is released.
